<paragraph blockId="1.[801,1453,780,1220]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis box="[839,920,781,804]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Notes. –</emphasis>
<collectionCode box="[928,948,780,804]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
strange circumstance is that 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Molluginaceae" genus="Paramollugo" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nudicaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Paramollugo nudicaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be an exceedingly rare species on 
<collectingCountry box="[1337,1447,812,836]" name="Mauritius" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
. Apparently, the only specimen of it ever collected on 
<collectingCountry box="[1348,1452,844,868]" name="Mauritius" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
during the nearly 250 years that have passed since Commerson collected there seems to be 
<emphasis box="[1085,1219,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Gueho 15575</emphasis>
(
<collectionCode box="[1233,1254,908,932]" country="United Kingdom" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15867" name="Royal Botanic Gardens" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" type="Herbarium">K</collectionCode>
), collected 
<date pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="1973-02-23">23 February 1973</date>
at Morne Brabant (SUKHORUKOv &amp; KUSHUNINA, 2016). This opens for the possibility of some kind of confusion as regards the locality or collector of the specimen. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="DORR" box="[831,976,1036,1060]" firstAuthor="DORR" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refId="ref1271" refString="DORR, L. J. (1997). Plant collectors in Madagascar and the Comoro Islands. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." type="book" year="1997">DORR (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, Commerson’s specimens “were labeled and distributed after his death and some confusion is known to have occurred with 
<collectionCode box="[953,967,1101,1124]" country="France" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15763" name="Museum National d' Histoire Naturelle, Paris (MNHN) - Vascular Plants" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" type="Herbarium">P</collectionCode>
. Sonnerat specimens”. The obvious alternative origin of the 
<typeStatus box="[939,984,1133,1157]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
specimen would be 
<collectingCountry box="[1197,1322,1132,1156]" name="Madagascar" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, where both 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:B57F879A6940FFD1FCD9FDDAFAC8FCF7:380960576940FFD1FCD9FB00FC1EFC97" box="[801,932,1164,1188]" country="Madagascar" municipality="Sonnerat" name="Commerson" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Commerson</location>
and 
<collectingMunicipality box="[985,1080,1164,1188]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Sonnerat</collectingMunicipality>
collected extensively, but any statement in that direction would have to remain speculation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
